&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>If you&amp;rsquo;ve ever wanted to build a terminal application that feels more like a proper UI than a wall of text, the &lt;a href="https://github.com/charmbracelet" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">charmbracelet&lt;/a> ecosystem is the way to go. I&amp;rsquo;ve been using it to build internal DevOps tools, and the developer experience is excellent. In this post, I&amp;rsquo;ll walk through building an interactive CLI tool using &lt;a href="https://github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Bubbletea&lt;/a> and &lt;a href="https://github.com/charmbracelet/huh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Huh&lt;/a>, the same libraries behind tools like &lt;code>gum&lt;/code> and &lt;code>soft-serve&lt;/code>.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>